@Maddie It’s an idea first proposed by Rex Parker, stated as: "If you include a proper noun in your grid that you cannot reasonably expect more than 1/4 of the solving public to have heard of, you must cross that noun with reasonably common words and phrases or very common names."

It came from a much-reviled 1-across clue that referenced Natick as simply a town at the 8th mile of the Boston Marathon, with some equally troublesome crossing clues that made it essentially indeterminate, and therefore against the implied “spirit” of crosswords.

The gist is that if you’re going to use an obscure word or trivia that most people wouldn’t know, you should cross that answer with more easy clues/words in order to give people a better chance of guessing the troublesome one correctly.

